Khar'Daan: The Sunken Necropolis

Deep in the desert, where warm brackish water rises beneath sandstone
shelves, lies Khar'Daan -- a city built to defeat decay that was itself
undone by water. Where the pyramids monumentalized sovereignty and the
oases administered survival, Khar'Daan preserved bodies, identities,
contracts, and dynastic legitimacy across generations. If the Great Oasis
taught the desert to measure water, Khar'Daan taught it to measure memory.

The Covenant of Salt and Flow

The Covenant of Salt and Flow bound preservation to infrastructure: the
dead of the great houses would be maintained here, and in return those
houses funded roads, cisterns, and water distribution. Every burial license
included a measured water contribution. Death was not private; it was
infrastructure. Early water-debt notation originated in these burial
accounts, later adapted for toll records across the oasis triad. Khar'Daan
also maintained mixed ritual mathematics for both pyramid traditions until
the twin sovereign rivalry forced an impossible neutrality.

The Ninth Meridian Aftershock

A failed eclipse rite destabilized shared cosmology. At Khar'Daan, sluice
crews altered calibrations, seal-priests invoked incompatible sequences,
and channels burst into the archive quarter. During the Week of Sundered
Measures, noble houses broke seals to retrieve ancestors, spreading
contamination. High priest Sethnekh refused full evacuation.

Perpetual Custody

Sethnekh codified a terrifying solution: the dead who served in life would
serve in death. Archives would be defended by bound intellects, and
sovereign legitimacy held in phylacteric reserve. This produced oathbound
revenant cohorts, annalist wraiths, and sentinel constructs keyed to
obsolete warrants. Sethnekh intended preservation. He achieved occupation.

The Dread Pharaoh

The entity called the Crown Without Breath is less a ruler than a
composite state assembled from dynastic remains and bound command glyphs.
Its three fused artifacts -- Solar Mask, Sealed Tide Cartouche, Night
Ledger Core -- command constructs and overwrite oathbindings. Destroying
it risks unleashing uncontrolled guardians across every desert route.

The dead do not rest here because they were never meant to. Perpetual
Custody outlived its authors, its context, and its purpose. The embalmers
still embalm. The archivists still index. No lawful authority has revoked
their duty.
